Anyway, shall I get him to meet you
in the parking lot at six?

83
00:05:37,200 --> 00:05:40,600
Sure. Yes. Thank you.
That would be great.

84
00:05:41,900 --> 00:05:42,800
- Okay
- Okay

85
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:49,100
Oh, yeah. It's all limo
rides for you, isn't it?

86
00:05:49,150 --> 00:05:52,800
Me, I get to take a ride home
with the geek squad.

87
00:06:02,400 --> 00:06:03,500
He is computer chip? Oh!

88
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:08,700
Hey, Hi!

89
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:15,400
You probably don't recognize me
standing upright but this
really is my better side.

90
00:06:16,300 --> 00:06:20,000
I'm Nola Devlin. You are computer chip, right?

91
00:06:20,040 --> 00:06:21,400
Is that a joke?

92
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:26,100
Apparently not a very good one.
Thank you for waiting for me.

93
00:06:26,140 --> 00:06:29,000
Joy told me you live
near me on the north-end

94
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:32,000
so I really appreciate...
the ride.

95
00:06:32,040 --> 00:06:34,800
You did offer to give a ride, didn't you?

96
00:06:34,840 --> 00:06:37,700
Well, I'd be happy to give you a ride.

97
00:06:37,500 --> 00:06:38,100
Okay

98
00:06:38,140 --> 00:06:40,000
You edit Belinda Apple's column.

99
00:06:40,100 --> 00:06:41,000
Yeah.

100
00:06:43,300 --> 00:06:45,800
So. Did you end up getting fired?

101
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:48,600
No, not yet. But I am sure
that that's in the works.

102
00:06:50,100 --> 00:06:51,100
Bad day?

103
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:57,000
When I was in the 6th grade a boy
asked me to a Halloween party.

104
00:06:57,600 --> 00:07:00,600
I went as a cheeseburger because
that's the only contume that fit.

105
00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:04,700
Well. When I got there I found out
that you were supposed to be

106
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:06,800
dressed as what you want
to be when you grew up.

107
00:07:07,500 --> 00:07:10,800
Yeah. Today was worse.
I don't wanna talk about it.

108
00:07:11,900 --> 00:07:13,800
And my car, the one that died...

109
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:16,800
My dad bought me that car
for my 16th birthday.

110
00:07:16,700 --> 00:07:18,600
You know, I mean...
That cat took me to college.

111
00:07:18,640 --> 00:07:23,000
I was to the Jersey Shore in that car.
That cat took me to
Boston to see Cold Play.

112
00:07:23,040 --> 00:07:27,400
I made out with Ronnie Spilman in that car.
That car defines me.

113
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:30,500
Defined you. Past tense.

114
00:07:30,700 --> 00:07:32,400
Hey, look. You know, change is good.

115
00:07:32,500 --> 00:07:34,800
Old car dies.
New car could be better.

116
00:07:34,840 --> 00:07:37,600
What about a... Porsche.

117
00:07:38,100 --> 00:07:40,100
That is my back-up fantasy car.

118
00:07:40,200 --> 00:07:41,400
Back-up fantasy?

119
00:07:41,700 --> 00:07:46,600
Well, my fantasy-fantasy car is a
powder-blue 55 thunderbird.

120
00:07:46,640 --> 00:07:50,100
I mean, if I had to break the bank,
that would be my sledgehammer.

121
00:07:50,140 --> 00:07:51,100
Now you're talking.

122
00:07:51,540 --> 00:07:56,400
Now I'm dellucinating.
Can't afford that car on my salary.

123
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,400
Don't let work get in the way of your dream.
I speak from my experience.

124
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:03,000
I am all about the dream and
so not about the job.

125
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:05,900
Girls like me don't drive cars like that.

126
00:08:05,940 --> 00:08:06,900
Says who?

127
00:08:06,940 --> 00:08:09,000
My low self-esteem.

128
00:08:11,500 --> 00:08:17,100
Well, maybe it's time for you to grow
up, take charge of your life and be all
that you can be.

129
00:08:19,300 --> 00:08:20,200
Oh, okay.

130
00:08:20,240 --> 00:08:23,700
It's the advice my father gives me.

131
00:08:23,800 --> 00:08:26,200
But hey, listen, if the
whole dream doesn't work for you,

132
00:08:26,240 --> 00:08:28,600
you can always do as he tells me
and demand change.

133
00:08:30,700 --> 00:08:31,600
This one. Right here.

134
00:08:31,640 --> 00:08:32,200
Right there?

135
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:33,100
Yeah.

136
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:40,100
Thank you for the ride.
It was very nice of you.

137
00:08:41,600 --> 00:08:42,900
Can I offer you anything for gas?

138
00:08:44,200 --> 00:08:45,300
No. I'm cool.

139
00:08:46,300 --> 00:08:47,200
All right.

140
00:08:48,900 --> 00:08:51,000
It's probably none of my business but...

141
00:08:52,600 --> 00:08:56,300
I think your father is wrong. I don't
think you can demand change from people.

142
00:08:56,200 --> 00:08:59,800
I think you have to... inspire it.
You know?

143
00:09:01,100 --> 00:09:02,500
Yeah.

144
00:09:09,600 --> 00:09:13,200
All right. Let's see what we got. You ready?

145
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:23,500
Dear Belinda.
This is my life. Or non-life.

146
00:09:23,500 --> 00:09:25,800
I am a plus-size woman
in her thirties

147
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:28,300
with a cat in a pastel
colored apartment.

148
00:09:28,340 --> 00:09:33,400
Could I be any more the stereotype?

149
00:09:33,800 --> 00:09:35,600
I'm under-appreciated at work.

150
00:09:35,640 --> 00:09:37,800
And the only physical contact I
get is from my cat.

151
00:09:38,600 --> 00:09:43,400
Am I hopeless? Can I get out of this rut?
Or should I just buy another cat?

152
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:47,700
Signed "Lifeless in Los Angeles".

153
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:54,200
All right, Belinda. What do you got?

154
00:09:55,300 --> 00:09:57,500
Dear Lifeless,

155
00:09:57,600 --> 00:10:03,400
Your cat must be tired of the pity-party
you've been throwing yourself everyday.

156
00:10:04,100 --> 00:10:08,800
Maybe if you didn't put yourself down
so much you wouldn't be so pathetic.

157
00:10:08,840 --> 00:10:11,300
You want a life? Get one.

158
00:10:12,300 --> 00:10:21,200
Grant yourself a wish to change. Then
stop complaining and do something.

159
00:10:24,800 --> 00:10:26,300
Yeah, I did something.

160
00:10:29,300 --> 00:10:29,800
What?

161
00:10:31,300 --> 00:10:33,400
Hi, Lory.

162
00:10:35,300 --> 00:10:37,200
Lory,

163
00:10:38,600 --> 00:10:42,100
you know how you said Shine
needs to distinguish itself

164
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:45,000
by adding an advice columnist
to address issues facing women today?

165
00:10:45,040 --> 00:10:47,400
I said I wanted a columnist
to answer all the dimwits

166
00:10:47,440 --> 00:10:49,400
who ask embarasing questions
about their sex lifes.

167
00:10:51,400 --> 00:10:54,300
Well, I answered your sample questions

168
00:10:54,340 --> 00:10:59,100
for the advice columnist in what
I believe is a biting and edgy way.

169
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:04,000
Oh, you're serious.

170
00:11:04,040 --> 00:11:06,100
I wanna write...

171
00:11:06,500 --> 00:11:08,100
So, write.

172
00:11:08,600 --> 00:11:12,000
...here. Lory, I wanna write here.

173
00:11:12,400 --> 00:11:17,100
Listen, I've been an assistant editor for
over a year. And before I came to Shine I wrote

174
00:11:17,140 --> 00:11:20,100
articles for my college paper.
Good stuff. I can do this.

175
00:11:20,140 --> 00:11:21,800
It's good to dream big.

176
00:11:22,900 --> 00:11:24,400
Thank you.

177
00:11:27,400 --> 00:11:31,900
Being a columnist is a very important,
very public position.

178
00:11:31,940 --> 00:11:35,200
It's the face of
the magazine.

179
00:11:35,240 --> 00:11:36,300
Right.

180
00:11:36,700 --> 00:11:38,500
You're not a face.

181
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:42,300
You are just a big girl
with a big dream.

182
00:11:43,400 --> 00:11:44,600
Nice try, though.

183
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:01,900
She wants a face.
I'll give her a face.

184
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:03,300
Bing!

185
00:12:14,400 --> 00:12:16,000
I'm hot.

186
00:12:32,200 --> 00:12:33,300
Hi, Lory.

187
00:12:33,340 --> 00:12:34,500
What's wrong with Belinda?

188
00:12:35,700 --> 00:12:36,700
What do you mean?

189
00:12:36,740 --> 00:12:38,600
I can't get her on the phone
to discuss the book.

190
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,300
If she doesn't call me back I'm
going to have to fly to London tomorrow.

191
00:12:41,340 --> 00:12:43,000
Is that really necessary?

192
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:47,000
This book is a huge deal. It will launch
a new division for the company.

193
00:12:47,040 --> 00:12:49,100
They're dumping a load of
money into promoting it.

194
00:12:49,300 --> 00:12:52,000
Book tour, TV, Oprah...
Belinda will be everywhere.

195
00:12:52,040 --> 00:12:53,100
In person?

196
00:12:53,140 --> 00:12:55,500
That's why they call them
"personal appearences".

197
00:12:55,540 --> 00:12:57,700
I'm gonna try to conference her in.
Hold on.

198
00:12:58,000 --> 00:12:59,000
No! Wait!

199
00:13:01,500 --> 00:13:03,300
What's that?

200
00:13:03,340 --> 00:13:04,200
Nothing.

201
00:13:04,240 --> 00:13:05,100
Hello!

202
00:13:05,140 --> 00:13:10,000
Belinda... Belinda, finally.
Hi. It's Lory and Nola.

203
00:13:10,200 --> 00:13:13,000
Hello, Lory. Hello Nola.
I'm actually just headed...

204
00:13:13,040 --> 00:13:14,060
At two in the morning?

205
00:13:14,100 --> 00:13:15,300
Yes... in. Just headed in.

206
00:13:16,400 --> 00:13:17,900
- Nola?
- Yeah!

207
00:13:18,100 --> 00:13:20,400
Do you wanna tell her
about our promotional plans?

208
00:13:21,300 --> 00:13:22,800
Is this about the book?

209
00:13:24,300 --> 00:13:29,200
Yes, it is, actually, Belinda.
They want you to come out here.

210
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:31,900
Well, that's impossible.
I'm in London.

211
00:13:32,900 --> 00:13:34,400
So, it'a a good thing we have planes.

212
00:13:35,300 --> 00:13:38,300
Yes, isn't it?
You know... I don't think I can make it.

213
00:13:38,340 --> 00:13:39,700
You don't even know when it is.

214
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:41,400
Oh, when is it?

215
00:13:41,440 --> 00:13:42,200
End of October.

216
00:13:42,240 --> 00:13:42,800
